Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.360 --> 00:00:02.290
- Welcome to the Huberman Lab Podcast,

00:00:02.290 --> 00:00:04.920
where we discuss science
and science-based tools

00:00:04.920 --> 00:00:06.307
for everyday life.

00:00:06.307 --> 00:00:09.190
[upbeat music]

00:00:09.190 --> 00:00:10.350
I'm Andrew Huberman,

00:00:10.350 --> 00:00:13.000
and I'm a professor of
neurobiology and ophthalmology

00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:14.940
at Stanford School of Medicine.

00:00:14.940 --> 00:00:17.280
Today's episode is about the biology,

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:20.760
psychology and practices
of social bonding.

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:23.740
From the day we are born
until the day we die,

00:00:23.740 --> 00:00:25.440
the quality of our social bonds

00:00:25.440 --> 00:00:28.280
dictates much of our quality of life.

00:00:28.280 --> 00:00:31.490
It should therefore be no
surprise that our brain,

00:00:31.490 --> 00:00:34.170
and indeed much of our
entire nervous system

00:00:34.170 --> 00:00:36.820
is wired for social bonds.

00:00:36.820 --> 00:00:40.400
Now social bonds occur
between infant and parent,

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:43.558
there even particular wiring
diagrams within the brain

00:00:43.558 --> 00:00:45.810
and spinal cord and body

00:00:45.810 --> 00:00:47.666
that are oriented towards
the specific bonds

00:00:47.666 --> 00:00:50.400
that occur between infant and mother,

00:00:50.400 --> 00:00:52.900
as well as infant and father.

00:00:52.900 --> 00:00:56.220
And we have specific brain
circuitries for friendship,

00:00:56.220 --> 00:00:58.830
specific brain circuitries
that are activated

00:00:58.830 --> 00:01:00.610
in romantic relationships.

00:01:00.610 --> 00:01:03.285
And as it goes, specific brain circuitries

00:01:03.285 --> 00:01:06.661
that are activated when we
break up with a romantic partner

00:01:06.661 --> 00:01:08.430
or when they break up with us,

00:01:08.430 --> 00:01:11.240
or when somebody passes away, moves away,

00:01:11.240 --> 00:01:15.580
or otherwise leaves our
lives in one form or another.

00:01:15.580 --> 00:01:17.770
Today, we are going to
talk about those brain

00:01:17.770 --> 00:01:19.470
and nervous system circuitries,

00:01:19.470 --> 00:01:21.450
we're also going to talk
about the neurochemicals

00:01:21.450 --> 00:01:24.300
and hormones that underlie their function.

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:26.930
And we are going to touch
on a number of important

00:01:26.930 --> 00:01:30.610
and actionable tools that you
can apply in everyday life.

00:01:30.610 --> 00:01:33.150
And because we are
headed into the holiday,

00:01:33.150 --> 00:01:35.880
the New Year and Christmas holiday,

00:01:35.880 --> 00:01:38.350
that you can deploy in
your various interactions

00:01:38.350 --> 00:01:40.070
with family members and friends.

00:01:40.070 --> 00:01:42.070
And should you not be spending time

00:01:42.070 --> 00:01:43.160
with family members and friends,

00:01:43.160 --> 00:01:44.940
today, we are also going to talk about

00:01:44.940 --> 00:01:46.680
how to achieve social bonds

00:01:46.680 --> 00:01:48.910
out of the context of family

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:51.340
and romantic partnership and friendship.

00:01:51.340 --> 00:01:54.150
So today's episode is going
to include a lot of science,

00:01:54.150 --> 00:01:55.850
a lot of actionable tools,

00:01:55.850 --> 00:01:57.790
and I'm confident that you will come away

00:01:57.790 --> 00:01:59.140
from today's episode

00:01:59.140 --> 00:02:02.640
with tremendous knowledge
about how you function.

00:02:02.640 --> 00:02:05.030
For instance, if you're an
introvert or an extrovert,

00:02:05.030 --> 00:02:05.863
why is that?

00:02:05.863 --> 00:02:08.280
Turns out there may be a
neurochemical basis for that.

00:02:08.280 --> 00:02:10.360
Maybe you're somebody that
really enjoys social media,

00:02:10.360 --> 00:02:11.710
maybe you're somebody that doesn't.

00:02:11.710 --> 00:02:14.740
Today I'm going to talk about
a gene or a set of genes

00:02:14.740 --> 00:02:17.132
that predicts whether or not
you will follow more people

00:02:17.132 --> 00:02:21.670
or seek out more online,
social interactions or fewer.

00:02:21.670 --> 00:02:23.760
Believe it or not, there's
biology around that now,

00:02:23.760 --> 00:02:25.770
and it's excellent peer reviewed work.

00:02:25.770 --> 00:02:29.000
We will also talk about
how bonds are broken,

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:30.797
and why breakups can be so painful,

00:02:30.797 --> 00:02:32.540
not just romantic breakups,

00:02:32.540 --> 00:02:35.220
but breakups with
friendships and coworkers,

00:02:35.220 --> 00:02:38.100
and how to move through
those more seamlessly.

00:02:38.100 --> 00:02:39.660
So regardless of your age,

